I used a decision tree for my forecast. I started my calculation before the match Croatia vs. Denmark. So Brazil (four possible upcoming games) has a lower probabilty to win compared to France (three possible upcoming games). The odds are self-made. Most of them are even or close to (cause you could already see underdogs playing well in round of 16). And odds for the final are always even to simplify the operation and because the final game can't be compared to the previous ones in terms of predictability IMO.

There are now a 'difficult path' and an 'easy path' to the final and the winner of the difficult path branch should not be more than a 2/3 favorite. So Belgium+Brazil+France+Uruguay(Another) = 65 and England(Another)+Spain = 35. Right now Brazil and France are joint favorites with about 20% each so 25 to Belgium and Uruguay, 15 to England and 20 to Spain. I fancy Belgium over Uruguay, but not by much, so I allocate 15 and 10 respectively leaving 25 for Another country (10 Uru + 15 Eng). I fancy Belgium over Spain outright, but being part of the easy branch gives Spain the edge.

Other countries, Switzerland and Belgium also get a boost now, as the bottom half of the right side (F1, E2, G2, H1) is going to be wide open pending Brazil winning Group E. The establishment of football world rankings goes back to 1993. Since that time, the winners and runners of each world cup has been as follows, with world cup rankings from the previous year in brackets: 1994 - Brazil (3); Italy (2) 1998 - France (7); Brazil (1) 2002 - Brazil (3); Germany (12) 2006 - Italy (12); France (5) 2010 - Spain (2); Netherlands (3) 2014 - Germany (2); Argentina (3) It does therefore seem that the winner is almost certain to come from the top 15. We can also see that former winners do tend to reach the final stages - Brazil, Argentina, Germany and Italy were all previous winners. Nevertheless, for a sport that has a relatively small number of countries that have ever won, it does seem that the Spanish and French victories shows that it is not an unthinkable for a team that has never won to succeed. I think there is a risk of overstating the home-nation effect: both Brazil and Germany failed to win in 2014 and 2006 respectively when they might have been expected to have had a good chance.

Bleacher reports's World Cup team rankings (linked below) list Germany, Brazil, Spain, and France as the top four in descending order. Hard to argue with that, and very unlikely that the winner won't be one of those four, though three other teams (Argentina, Belgium, and Uruguay) could rise to the occasion. On the global stage of the World Cup, the competition is usually too fierce, and pressure too intense, for third-tier teams with only one or two world-class stars (Portugal, England, Poland) to advance to the finals.
